context: <a1_0>In <b5_0>1663<b5_0/><a1_0/> at the Archbishop of Canterbury's residence, <a0_0><b4_0>Lambeth Palace<b4_0/><a0_0/>, a Gothic hammerbeam roof was built to replace that destroyed when the building was sacked during the English Civil War. Also in <a2_0><b6_0>the late 17th century<b6_0/><a2_0/>, some discrete Gothic details appeared on new construction at Oxford University and Cambridge University, notably on Tom Tower at Christ Church, Oxford, by <a3_0><b7_0>Christopher Wren<b7_0/><a3_0/>. It is not easy to decide whether these instances were Gothic survival or early appearances of Gothic revival.
